  <h2 id="f6">6. Finance-Based Pricing Advisor</h2>
  <p>Should Hire Space differentiate commission rates based on whether a booking is DAS or DAC?</p>

  <h3>How DAS and DAC Work (Per Booking)</h3>
  <div class="box">
    <p>Every booking is either DAS or DAC. This is not a venue-level classification; it's set per booking.</p>
    <table>
      <tr><th></th><th>DAS (Deduct at Source)</th><th>DAC (Deduct at Conclusion)</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Payment flow</td><td>Hire Space collects full payment from client, deducts commission, pays venue the remainder</td><td>Hire Space pays the full booking amount to the venue, then invoices the venue for commission afterwards</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Commission capture</td><td>Guaranteed â€” deducted before venue is paid</td><td>At risk â€” Hire Space must chase the venue for payment</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hire Space cash flow risk</td><td>Low (commission secured upfront)</td><td>High (commission is owed, not held)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Venue experience</td><td>Receives net amount; simpler, more managed</td><td>Receives full amount; more autonomy, but then owes commission</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>The Opportunity</h3>
  <div class="box">
    <p>DAS and DAC bookings carry fundamentally different risk profiles for Hire Space. With DAS, commission is guaranteed. With DAC, there's a real collection risk, plus the overhead of invoicing and chasing. Yet both currently carry the same commission rate.</p>
    <p>This creates an opportunity: <strong>price according to the risk and service level each model requires.</strong></p>
  </div>

  <h3>Recommendation: Yes, but carefully</h3>
  <div class="box box-green">
    <h4>Option A: Lower DAS commission (incentivise venues toward DAS)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Reduce commission on DAS bookings by 1-2% vs DAC</li>
      <li>Rationale: DAS is lower risk for Hire Space (guaranteed commission capture, no chasing). The saving can be passed to venues as an incentive.</li>
      <li>Venues that prefer managed payments get a financial reward for choosing the model that's cheaper for Hire Space to operate</li>
      <li><strong>Revenue impact:</strong> Lower margin per DAS booking, but higher collection certainty and lower admin cost. Net positive if it shifts volume toward DAS.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Option B: Higher DAC commission (price in the collection risk)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Increase commission on DAC bookings by 1-2% to reflect the higher operational cost and collection risk</li>
      <li>Venues that want to receive the full amount upfront pay a premium for that flexibility</li>
      <li>Position as: "DAC gives you full payment control, DAS gives you a better rate"</li>
      <li><strong>Revenue impact:</strong> Higher margin on the riskier model. May nudge some venues toward DAS.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Option C: Tiered DAS with payment speed SLA</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Offer DAS bookings with a guaranteed payment SLA (e.g. venue paid within 7 days of event) at current commission</li>
      <li>Standard DAS (no SLA guarantee) at a slightly lower commission</li>
      <li>This adds value without changing the fundamental model</li>
      <li><strong>Revenue impact:</strong> Premium for speed. Differentiates Hire Space from competitors.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h3>Prerequisites (Do NOT launch pricing changes before these)</h3>
  <div class="box box-warn">
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Fix the payment infrastructure first.</strong> You cannot promise payment SLAs if your finance tools are manual and error-prone. Build the 3 priority tools first.</li>
      <li><strong>Measure current DAS vs DAC split.</strong> What percentage of bookings are each? What's the actual collection rate and cycle time on DAC invoices? You need this data to model the impact.</li>
      <li><strong>Understand venue sensitivity.</strong> Talk to 5-10 venues before changing rates. Some may not care about 1-2%; others will.</li>
      <li><strong>Legal review.</strong> Changing commission terms has contractual implications. Ensure existing agreements allow for differentiated pricing by booking type.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <h3>Risk Assessment</h3>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Risk</th><th>Likelihood</th><th>Mitigation</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Venue pushback on differentiated rates</td><td>Medium</td><td>Frame as choice: "pick the model that suits you, pricing reflects the cost to operate each"</td></tr>
